IPUIN481L020000000.title: Labor Compensation for Transportation and Warehousing: Air Transportation (NAICS 481) in the United States
IPUIN481L020000000.notes: Labor compensation, defined as payroll plus supplemental payments, is a measure of the cost to the employer of securing the services of labor. Payroll includes salaries, wages, commissions, dismissal pay, bonuses, vacation and sick leave pay, and compensation in kind. Supplemental payments include both legally required expenditures and payments for voluntary programs. The legally required portion consists primarily of federal old age and survivors’ insurance, unemployment compensation, and workers’ compensation. Payments for voluntary programs include all programs not specifically required by legislation, such as the employer portion of private health insurance and pension plans.
IPUIN481L020000000.path: Database/Population, Employment, & Labor Markets/Productivity & Costs/Transportation and Warehousing

IPUIN481M000000000.title: Total Factor Productivity for Transportation and Warehousing: Air Transportation (NAICS 481) in the United States
IPUIN481M000000000.notes: Total factor productivity is the efficiency at which combined inputs are used to produce output of goods and services. The total factor productivity indexes do not measure the specific contributions of capital, labor, and intermediate inputs. Rather, they reflect the joint influences on economic growth of a number of factors that are not specifically accounted for on the input side, including technological change, returns to scale, improved skills of the workforce, better management techniques, or other efficiency improvements.
IPUIN481M000000000.path: Database/Population, Employment, & Labor Markets/Productivity & Costs/Transportation and Warehousing

IPUIN484L020000000.title: Labor Compensation for Transportation and Warehousing: Truck Transportation (NAICS 484) in the United States
IPUIN484L020000000.notes: Labor compensation, defined as payroll plus supplemental payments, is a measure of the cost to the employer of securing the services of labor. Payroll includes salaries, wages, commissions, dismissal pay, bonuses, vacation and sick leave pay, and compensation in kind. Supplemental payments include both legally required expenditures and payments for voluntary programs. The legally required portion consists primarily of federal old age and survivors’ insurance, unemployment compensation, and workers’ compensation. Payments for voluntary programs include all programs not specifically required by legislation, such as the employer portion of private health insurance and pension plans.
IPUIN484L020000000.path: Database/Population, Employment, & Labor Markets/Productivity & Costs/Transportation and Warehousing

IPUIN484U120000000.title: Hourly Compensation for Transportation and Warehousing: Truck Transportation (NAICS 484) in the United States

Wage and salary accruals consist of the monetary remuneration of employees. IPUIN491U110000000.title: Labor Compensation for Transportation and Warehousing: Postal Service (NAICS 491) in the United States
IPUIN491U110000000.notes: Labor compensation, defined as payroll plus supplemental payments, is a measure of the cost to the employer of securing the services of labor. Payroll includes salaries, wages, commissions, dismissal pay, bonuses, vacation and sick leave pay, and compensation in kind. Supplemental payments include both legally required expenditures and payments for voluntary programs. The legally required portion consists primarily of federal old age and survivors’ insurance, unemployment compensation, and workers’ compensation. Payments for voluntary programs include all programs not specifically required by legislation, such as the employer portion of private health insurance and pension plans.
IPUIN491U110000000.path: Database/Population, Employment, & Labor Markets/Productivity & Costs/Transportation and Warehousing

IPUIN491U120000000.title: Hourly Compensation for Transportation and Warehousing: Postal Service (NAICS 491) in the United States
IPUIN491U120000000.notes: Hourly compensation is the sum of wage and salary accruals and supplements to wages and salaries per hour of labor services used to produce output. Wage and salary accruals consist of the monetary remuneration of employees. Supplements to wages and salaries consist of employer contributions for social insurance and employer payments (including payments in kind) to private pension and profit-sharing plans, group health and life insurance plans, privately administered workers' compensation plans.
IPUIN491U120000000.path: Database/Population, Employment, & Labor Markets/Productivity & Costs/Transportation and Warehousing

IPUIN4841L020000000.title: Labor Compensation for Transportation and Warehousing: General Freight Trucking (NAICS 4841) in the United States

Supplemental payments include both legally required expenditures and payments for voluntary programs. The legally required portion consists primarily of federal old age and survivors’ insurance, unemployment compensation, and workers’ compensation. Payments for voluntary programs include all programs not specifically required by legislation, such as the employer portion of private health insurance and pension plans.

IPUIN4911L020000000.title: Labor Compensation for Transportation and Warehousing: Postal Service (NAICS 4911) in the United States
IPUIN4911L020000000.notes: Labor compensation, defined as payroll plus supplemental payments, is a measure of the cost to the employer of securing the services of labor. Payroll includes salaries, wages, commissions, dismissal pay, bonuses, vacation and sick leave pay, and compensation in kind. Supplemental payments include both legally required expenditures and payments for voluntary programs. The legally required portion consists primarily of federal old age and survivors’ insurance, unemployment compensation, and workers’ compensation. Payments for voluntary programs include all programs not specifically required by legislation, such as the employer portion of private health insurance and pension plans.
IPUIN4911L020000000.path: Database/Population, Employment, & Labor Markets/Productivity & Costs/Transportation and Warehousing

IPUIN4931L020000000.title: Labor Compensation for Transportation and Warehousing: Warehousing and Storage (NAICS 4931) in the United States
IPUIN4931L020000000.notes: Labor compensation, defined as payroll plus supplemental payments, is a measure of the cost to the employer of securing the services of labor. Payroll includes salaries, wages, commissions, dismissal pay, bonuses, vacation and sick leave pay, and compensation in kind. Supplemental payments include both legally required expenditures and payments for voluntary programs. The legally required portion consists primarily of federal old age and survivors’ insurance, unemployment compensation, and workers’ compensation. Payments for voluntary programs include all programs not specifically required by legislation, such as the employer portion of private health insurance and pension plans.
IPUIN4931L020000000.path: Database/Population, Employment, & Labor Markets/Productivity & Costs/Transportation and Warehousing

IPUIN4931U120000000.title: Hourly Compensation for Transportation and Warehousing: Warehousing and Storage (NAICS 4931) in the United States
IPUIN4931U120000000.notes: Hourly compensation is the sum of wage and salary accruals and supplements to wages and salaries per hour of labor services used to produce output. Wage and salary accruals consist of the monetary remuneration of employees. Supplements to wages and salaries consist of employer contributions for social insurance and employer payments (including payments in kind) to private pension and profit-sharing plans, group health and life insurance plans, privately administered workers' compensation plans.
IPUIN4931U120000000.path: Database/Population, Employment, & Labor Markets/Productivity & Costs/Transportation and Warehousing

IPUIN48411L020000000.title: Labor Compensation for Transportation and Warehousing: General Freight Trucking, Local (NAICS 48411) in the United States
IPUIN48411L020000000.notes: Labor compensation, defined as payroll plus supplemental payments, is a measure of the cost to the employer of securing the services of labor. Payroll includes salaries, wages, commissions, dismissal pay, bonuses, vacation and sick leave pay, and compensation in kind. Supplemental payments include both legally required expenditures and payments for voluntary programs. The legally required portion consists primarily of federal old age and survivors’ insurance, unemployment compensation, and workers’ compensation. Payments for voluntary programs include all programs not specifically required by legislation, such as the employer portion of private health insurance and pension plans.
IPUIN48411L020000000.path: Database/Population, Employment, & Labor Markets/Productivity & Costs/Transportation and Warehousing

IPUIN48421U110000000.title: Labor Compensation for Transportation and Warehousing: Used Household and Office Goods Moving (NAICS 48421) in the United States
IPUIN48421U110000000.notes: Labor compensation, defined as payroll plus supplemental payments, is a measure of the cost to the employer of securing the services of labor. Payroll includes salaries, wages, commissions, dismissal pay, bonuses, vacation and sick leave pay, and compensation in kind. Supplemental payments include both legally required expenditures and payments for voluntary programs. The legally required portion consists primarily of federal old age and survivors’ insurance, unemployment compensation, and workers’ compensation. Payments for voluntary programs include all programs not specifically required by legislation, such as the employer portion of private health insurance and pension plans.
IPUIN48421U110000000.path: Database/Population, Employment, & Labor Markets/Productivity & Costs/Transportation and Warehousing

IPUIN48421U120000000.title: Hourly Compensation for Transportation and Warehousing: Used Household and Office Goods Moving (NAICS 48421) in the United States
IPUIN48421U120000000.notes: Hourly compensation is the sum of wage and salary accruals and supplements to wages and salaries per hour of labor services used to produce output. Wage and salary accruals consist of the monetary remuneration of employees. Supplements to wages and salaries consist of employer contributions for social insurance and employer payments (including payments in kind) to private pension and profit-sharing plans, group health and life insurance plans, privately administered workers' compensation plans.
IPUIN48421U120000000.path: Database/Population, Employment, & Labor Markets/Productivity & Costs/Transportation and Warehousing

IPUIN49111L020000000.title: Labor Compensation for Transportation and Warehousing: Postal Service (NAICS 49111) in the United States
IPUIN49111L020000000.notes: Labor compensation, defined as payroll plus supplemental payments, is a measure of the cost to the employer of securing the services of labor. Payroll includes salaries, wages, commissions, dismissal pay, bonuses, vacation and sick leave pay, and compensation in kind. Supplemental payments include both legally required expenditures and payments for voluntary programs. The legally required portion consists primarily of federal old age and survivors’ insurance, unemployment compensation, and workers’ compensation. Payments for voluntary programs include all programs not specifically required by legislation, such as the employer portion of private health insurance and pension plans.
IPUIN49111L020000000.path: Database/Population, Employment, & Labor Markets/Productivity & Costs/Transportation and Warehousing

IPUIN49111U120000000.title: Hourly Compensation for Transportation and Warehousing: Postal Service (NAICS 49111) in the United States
IPUIN49111U120000000.notes: Hourly compensation is the sum of wage and salary accruals and supplements to wages and salaries per hour of labor services used to produce output. Wage and salary accruals consist of the monetary remuneration of employees. Supplements to wages and salaries consist of employer contributions for social insurance and employer payments (including payments in kind) to private pension and profit-sharing plans, group health and life insurance plans, privately administered workers' compensation plans.
IPUIN49111U120000000.path: Database/Population, Employment, & Labor Markets/Productivity & Costs/Transportation and Warehousing

IPUIN49111U121000000.title: Hourly Compensation for Transportation and Warehousing: Postal Service (NAICS 49111) in the United States

Wage and salary accruals consist of the monetary remuneration of employees. Supplements to wages and salaries consist of employer contributions for social insurance and employer payments (including payments in kind) to private pension and profit-sharing plans, group health and life insurance plans, privately administered workers' compensation plans.
IPUIN49111U121000000.path: Database/Population, Employment, & Labor Markets/Productivity & Costs/Transportation and Warehousing

IPUIN484230L020000000.title: Labor Compensation for Transportation and Warehousing: Specialized Freight (Except Used Goods) Trucking, Long-Distance (NAICS 484230) in the United States
IPUIN484230L020000000.notes: Labor compensation, defined as payroll plus supplemental payments, is a measure of the cost to the employer of securing the services of labor. Payroll includes salaries, wages, commissions, dismissal pay, bonuses, vacation and sick leave pay, and compensation in kind. Supplemental payments include both legally required expenditures and payments for voluntary programs. The legally required portion consists primarily of federal old age and survivors’ insurance, unemployment compensation, and workers’ compensation. Payments for voluntary programs include all programs not specifically required by legislation, such as the employer portion of private health insurance and pension plans.
IPUIN484230L020000000.path: Database/Population, Employment, & Labor Markets/Productivity & Costs/Transportation and Warehousing

IPUIN484230U120000000.title: Hourly Compensation for Transportation and Warehousing: Specialized Freight (Except Used Goods) Trucking, Long-Distance (NAICS 484230) in the United States
IPUIN484230U120000000.notes: Hourly compensation is the sum of wage and salary accruals and supplements to wages and salaries per hour of labor services used to produce output. Wage and salary accruals consist of the monetary remuneration of employees. Supplements to wages and salaries consist of employer contributions for social insurance and employer payments (including payments in kind) to private pension and profit-sharing plans, group health and life insurance plans, privately administered workers' compensation plans.
IPUIN484230U120000000.path: Database/Population, Employment, & Labor Markets/Productivity & Costs/Transportation and Warehousing

IPUIN491110L020000000.title: Labor Compensation for Transportation and Warehousing: Postal Service (NAICS 491110) in the United States
IPUIN491110L020000000.notes: Labor compensation, defined as payroll plus supplemental payments, is a measure of the cost to the employer of securing the services of labor. Payroll includes salaries, wages, commissions, dismissal pay, bonuses, vacation and sick leave pay, and compensation in kind. Supplemental payments include both legally required expenditures and payments for voluntary programs. The legally required portion consists primarily of federal old age and survivors’ insurance, unemployment compensation, and workers’ compensation. Payments for voluntary programs include all programs not specifically required by legislation, such as the employer portion of private health insurance and pension plans.
IPUIN491110L020000000.path: Database/Population, Employment, & Labor Markets/Productivity & Costs/Transportation and Warehousing

IPUIN491110U120000000.title: Hourly Compensation for Transportation and Warehousing: Postal Service (NAICS 491110) in the United States
IPUIN491110U120000000.notes: Hourly compensation is the sum of wage and salary accruals and supplements to wages and salaries per hour of labor services used to produce output. Wage and salary accruals consist of the monetary remuneration of employees. Supplements to wages and salaries consist of employer contributions for social insurance and employer payments (including payments in kind) to private pension and profit-sharing plans, group health and life insurance plans, privately administered workers' compensation plans.
IPUIN491110U120000000.path: Database/Population, Employment, & Labor Markets/Productivity & Costs/Transportation and Warehousing

IPUIN493110L010000000.path: Database/Population, Employment, & Labor Markets/Productivity & Costs/Transportation and Warehousing

IPUIN493110L020000000.title: Labor Compensation for Transportation and Warehousing: General Warehousing and Storage (NAICS 493110) in the United States
IPUIN493110L020000000.notes: Labor compensation, defined as payroll plus supplemental payments, is a measure of the cost to the employer of securing the services of labor. Payroll includes salaries, wages, commissions, dismissal pay, bonuses, vacation and sick leave pay, and compensation in kind. Supplemental payments include both legally required expenditures and payments for voluntary programs. The legally required portion consists primarily of federal old age and survivors’ insurance, unemployment compensation, and workers’ compensation. Payments for voluntary programs include all programs not specifically required by legislation, such as the employer portion of private health insurance and pension plans.
IPUIN493110L020000000.path: Database/Population, Employment, & Labor Markets/Productivity & Costs/Transportation and Warehousing

IPUIN493110U120000000.title: Hourly Compensation for Transportation and Warehousing: General Warehousing and Storage (NAICS 493110) in the United States
IPUIN493110U120000000.notes: Hourly compensation is the sum of wage and salary accruals and supplements to wages and salaries per hour of labor services used to produce output. Wage and salary accruals consist of the monetary remuneration of employees. Supplements to wages and salaries consist of employer contributions for social insurance and employer payments (including payments in kind) to private pension and profit-sharing plans, group health and life insurance plans, privately administered workers' compensation plans.
IPUIN493110U120000000.path: Database/Population, Employment, & Labor Markets/Productivity & Costs/Transportation and Warehousing
